This paper focuses on the usage and impact of automated static analysis tools (ASATs) in software development, which falls under the software engineering (cs.SE) sub-category. The paper specifically analyzes the usage of PMD, which is a tool for detecting common programming flaws, and its impact on software quality, which also falls under the programming languages (cs.PL) and software engineering (cs.SE) sub-categories. The paper also involves analyzing the commit history of open source projects, which falls under the software engineering (cs.SE) and software maintenance and evolution (cs.SW) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper involves analyzing trends and changes in warning types and severities, which falls under the cryptography and security (cs.CR) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves statistical analysis, which falls under the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
